    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In that case, I'll strip away the goblin metaphors and get to the scientific definition.\n\nA statistically significant result in a clinical trial means that the observed effect is unlikely to be due to chance, and the p-value is below a certain threshold, usually 0.05. This threshold is the probability of obtaining the observed result (or more extreme) by chance, assuming that the null hypothesis is true.\n\nIn other words, if the p-value is below 0.05, it indicates that the observed effect is statistically significant, and it's unlikely that the result is due to random chance. This is often denoted as \"p < 0.05\" in formal writing.\n\nTo be more precise, the definition of statistical significance can be stated as follows:\n\n\"A result is statistically significant if the p-value is less than the chosen significance level (usually 0.05), indicating that the observed effect is unlikely to be due to chance.\"\n\nNow, go forth and write that exam question with confidence!",
